kton biomass (as chlorophyll {\textless}em{\textgreater}a{\textless}/em{\textgreater}) was apparently controlled by water temperature and P availability (TN:TP ratio and dissolved P). Water transparency (as Secchi depth) was strongly and negatively influenced by chlorophyll {\textless}em{\textgreater}a{\textless}/em{\textgreater} concentration. {\textless}em{\textgreater}Cylindrospermopsis raciborskii{\textless}/em{\textgreater} abilities to compete for P and light seem to be important factors determining its success and dominance in this low P coastal ecosystem. The fluctuating P supply, probably associated to sediment resuspension by wind in this shallow waterbody, is an advantageous factor for cyanobacteria and has an important role in chlorophyll {\textless}em{\textgreater}a{\textless}/em{\textgreater} dynamics. Thus, high chlorophyll {\textless}em{\textgreater}a{\textless}/em{\textgreater} concentration in this subtropical lake seems to be related to the P-limited condition, shallowness and low water column transparency, which are probably favouring the dominance of {\textless}em{\textgreater}C. raciborskii{\textless}/em{\textgreater}, especially in higher summer temperatures, and leading to high chlorophyll {\textless}em{\textgreater}a{\textless}/em{\textgreater} concentration even in a low dissolved nutrient environment.{\textless}/p{\textgreater}{\textless}/p{\textgreater}},
