hanogenic populations corresponded well to the methane production rates determined by incubation with either [14C]acetate or [14C]bicarbonate. Methanogenesis from acetate accounted for almost all of the total methane production, which concurs with the predominance of acetoclastic Methanosaeta spp. that represented on average 91{\%} of the archaeal population. Significant hydrogenotrophic methanogenesis was found only in the organically enriched upper 2 cm of the sediment, where the probably hydrogenotrophic relatives of the methanogenic endosymbiont of P. nasuta, accounting on average for 7{\%} of the archaeal population, were also detected.},
author = {{Zepp Falz}, K. and Holliger, C. and Gro{\ss}kopf, R. and Liesack, W. and Nozhevnikova, A. N. and M{\"{u}}ller, B. and Wehrli, B. and Hahn, D.},
