@article{Raven1998,
abstract = {1. Picophytoplankton are planktonic photosynthetic O-2-evolvers that$\backslash$ncan pass through 2 mu m-diameter pores; they include prokaryotic$\backslash$n(eubacterial) and eukaryotic members and occur in freshwater and$\backslash$nmarine habitats. There are no photosynthetic reproductive and dispersal$\backslash$nstages of benthic macrophytes of picoplanktonic size. The picophytoplankton$\backslash$ncondition appears to be derived and polyphyletic in both prokaryotes$\backslash$nand eukaryotes. 2. Picophytoplankton are among the smallest free-living$\backslash$ncells, despite having to contain the photosynthetic apparatus, which$\backslash$noccupies about half of the cell volume, as well as core cellular$\backslash$nmachinery. The size of the smallest prokaryotic (0.6 mu m diameter)$\backslash$nand eukaryotic (0.95 mu m diameter) picophytoplankton are close to$\backslash$nthe minimum possible size estimated from the occurrence of non-scalable$\backslash$nessential components such as the genome and plasmalemma and other$\backslash$nmembranes. 3. Picophytoplankton cells have advantages relative to$\backslash$nlarger phytoplankton cells in terms of resource acquisition and the$\backslash$nsubsequent use of the resources in catalysing cell growth and reproduction.$\backslash$nThe smaller package effect in light harvesting means smaller resource$\backslash$n(energy, C, N, Fe, Mn, Cu) costs of photon harvesting and transformation$\backslash$ninto chemical energy in small than in large cells. The smaller diffusion$\backslash$nboundary layer around small cells, coupled with smaller nutrient$\backslash$nfluxes per unit plasmalemma area needed to attain a given fraction$\backslash$nof the maximum specific growth rate in smaller cells, increases the$\backslash$navailability of low concentrations of nutrients to small relative$\backslash$nto larger cells. If the supply of CO, to the core photosynthetic$\backslash$ncarboxylase ribulose bisphosphate carboxylase-oxygenase is purely$\backslash$nby diffusion then smaller cells could satisfy their catalytic requirements$\backslash$nwith less of this enzyme whose synthesis has high energy, C and N$\backslash$ncosts. Overall, resources can be acquired, and used in growth, more$\backslash$neffectively in smaller than in larger cells. 4. Some factors work$\backslash$nagainst the conclusion in (3.) but, in most habitats, do not negate$\backslash$nthese conclusions. Examples related to non-scalable essential cell$\backslash$ncomponents are the use of energy, C, N and P in the genome and of$\backslash$nenergy, C, N, P and Fe in the plasma membrane. Transport-related$\backslash$nfactors include the increased potential cell volume-specific leakage$\backslash$nof accumulated resources, and the greater cell volume-specific energy$\backslash$ncosts of motility at a given speed, in smaller than in larger cells.$\backslash$nThe smaller package effect in smaller cells involves a greater potential$\backslash$nfor photodamage by both photosynthetically active radiation and by$\backslash$nUV-B. 5. Picophytoplankton occurrence is also a function of factors$\backslash$nwhich lead to cell loss. Factors such as sinking out of the euphotic$\backslash$nzone and parasitism by eukaryotes such as chytrids are less significant$\backslash$nfor picophytoplankton than for larger cells, whereas viral parasitism$\backslash$nand grazing by appropriately sized grazers are likely to be at least$\backslash$nas great for picophytoplankton as for larger cells. 6. The totality$\backslash$nof the effects mentioned in (3.) above suggests that picophytoplankton$\backslash$nshould generally have higher specific growth rates (probably) in$\backslash$nresource-saturated (photons, C, N, P, Fe, etc.) and (certainly) in$\backslash$nresource-limited environments than do larger cells. The distribution$\backslash$nof picophytoplankton is certainly consistent with their ability to$\backslash$ncapitalize on resource-limited environments: they contribute a larger$\backslash$nfraction of biomass and productivity relative to larger cells in$\backslash$nlow-nutrient than in high-nutrient environments, and in low-light$\backslash$n(e.g. the deep chlorophyll maximum) than in high-light environments.$\backslash$n7. Sexual reproduction is apparently rare in picophytoplankton, with$\backslash$nimplications for species definition. There are probably relatively$\backslash$nfew species (hundreds or thousands) with very wide biogeographical$\backslash$nranges in marine or in freshwater habitats. The small size and (probably)$\backslash$nlow biodiversity means large numbers of individuals worldwide, e.g.$\backslash$nc.10(26) individuals of the commonest species of the marine cyanobacterium$\backslash$nSynechococcus. Picophytoplankton contribute at least one-tenth (i.e.$\backslash$nin excess of 3 Pg C per year) to global aquatic net primary productivity.$\backslash$n},
